

<section xml:id="Ch2Sec2LinearIndependence">
  <title>Linear independence</title>
  <definition>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A list of vectors <m>\ve{v}_1, \ve{v}_2, \ldots, \ve{v}_n</m> in a vector space <m>V</m> is called
        <term>linearly independent</term> if the equation
        <men xml:id="lin_independence_eqn">
          k_1 \ve{v}_1 + k_2 \ve{v}_2 + \cdots k_n \ve{v}_n = \ve{0}
        </men>
        has only the trivial solution <m>k_1 = k_2 = \cdots = k_n = 0</m>.
        Otherwise, the list of vectors <m>\ve{v}_1, \ve{v}_2, \ldots, \ve{v}_n</m> is called
        <term>linearly dependent</term>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <remark xml:id="remark_about_lin_dependence">
    <p>
      Suppose one of the vectors in the collection <m>\ve{v}_1</m>,
      <m>\ve{v}_2</m>,
      <m>\ldots</m>, <m>\ve{v}_n</m> is the zero vector <m>\ve{0}</m>;
      for instance suppose <m>\ve{v}_1 = \ve{0}</m>.
      Then the vectors must be linearly dependent,
      since the equation <xref ref="lin_independence_eqn" /> has the nontrivial solution <m>k_1 = 1</m>,
      <m>k_2 = k_2 = \cdots = k_n = 0</m>.
      So: <em>a list of linearly independent vectors never contains the zero vector!</em>
    </p>
  </remark>

  <remark xml:id="crit_ind">
    <p>
      The criterion for a list of vectors
      <m>\ve{v}_1, \ve{v}_2, \ldots, \ve{v}_n</m> to be linearly independent,
      <me>
        k_1 \ve{v}_1 + k_2 \ve{v}_2 + \cdots k_n \ve{v}_n = \ve{0}  \Rightarrow  k_1 = k_2 = \cdots = k_n = 0
      </me>
      is clearly equivalent to the criterion:
      <p>
         All of the <m>(\ve{v}_i)</m> are nonzero and none of them can be expressed as a nontrivial linear combination of the others. In fact, this seemingly obvious remark will be the starting point for many future proofs concerning linear independence!
       </p>
    </p>
  </remark>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Prove this last remark.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <example>
    <statement>
    <p>
      The list of vectors <m>\ve{f}_1 = (-1, \, 2)</m>,
      <m>\ve{f}_2 = (1, \,1)</m> from <xref ref="three_vectors_spanning_R2_example">Example</xref>
      is linearly independent, because the equation
      <me>
        k_1 (-1, \, 2) + k_2 (1, \, 1) = (0, \, 0)
      </me>
      is equivalent to the system of equations
      <men xml:id="system_from_r2_example">
       -k_1 + k_2 = 0, \quad 2k_1 + k_2 = 0
      </men>
      which has only the trivial solution <m>k_1 = 0</m> and <m>k_2 = 0</m>.
    </p>


    </statement>
  </example>

   <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Check that <xref ref="system_from_r2_example" /> has only the trivial solution.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

  <example xml:id="example_about_lin_dep_1">
    <statement>
    <p>
      The list of vectors <m>\ve{f}_1 = (-1, \, 2)</m>,
      <m>\ve{f}_2 = (1, \,1)</m>,
      <m>\ve{f}_3 = (2, \, -1)</m> from <xref ref="three_vectors_spanning_R2_example">Example</xref>
      is linearly dependent, because the equation
      <men xml:id="eqn_to_check_lin_ind">
        k_1 (-1, \, 2) + k_2 (1, \, 1) + k_3 (2, \, -1) = (0, \, 0)
      </men>
      is equivalent to the system of equations
      <men xml:id="system_from_r2_example_new">
       -k_1 + k_2 + 2k_3 = 0, \quad 2k_1 + k_2 - k_3 = 0
      </men>
      which has a one-dimensional vector space of solutions parameterized by <m>t</m>,
      <men xml:id="supposed_soln">
        k_1 = t, \, k_2 = -t, \, k_3 = t,  t \in \mathbb{R}
      </men>.
    </p>

    <p>
      For instance, for <m>t=2</m>, we have
      <me>
        2 (-1, \, 2) - 2 (1, \, 1) + 2 (2, \, -1) = (0, \, 0)
      </me>
      so that <xref ref="eqn_to_check_lin_ind" /> has nontrivial solutions.
    </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Check that <xref ref="system_from_r2_example_new" /> has the solution set <xref ref="supposed_soln" />.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

  <example xml:id="new_basis_for_poly_3">
    <statement>
      <p>
        The list of polynomials
        <me>
          \ve{q}_0(x) := 1, \,\, \ve{q}_1(x) := x, \,\, \ve{q}_2(x) := 2x^2 - 1, \,\, \ve{q}_3(x) := 4x^3 - 3x
        </me>
        from <xref ref="chebyshev_example">Example</xref>
        is linearly independent in <m>\Poly_3</m>.
        This is because the equation
        <me>
          k_0 \ve{q}_0 + k_1 \ve{q}_1 + k_2 \ve{q}_2 + k_3 \ve{q}_3 = \ve{0}
        </me>
        becomes the following equation between polynomials:
        <me>
          4k_3 x^3 + 2k_2 x^2 + (-3k_3 + k_1) x + (-k_2 + k_0) = 0
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        This is equivalent to the following system of equations,
        <me>
          4k_3 = 0, \quad 2k_2 = 0, \quad -3 k_3 + k_1 = 0, \quadk_0 - k_2 = 0
        </me>
        which has only the trivial solution <m>k_0 = k_1 = k_2 = k_3 = 0</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <p>
    At the moment,
    the definition of a list of vectors being <sq>linearly dependent</sq> is that the list is <sq>not linearly independent</sq>!
    That might get your head in a knot.
    Here is a more straightforward way to think about linearly depdendent lists of vectors.
  </p>

  <proposition xml:id="lin_dependence_prop">
    <title>Linear Combination of Preceding Vectors</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>\ve{v}_1</m>, <m>\ve{v}_2</m>, <m>\ldots</m>,
        <m>\ve{v}_n</m> be a list of vectors in a vector space <m>V</m>.
        The following statements are equivalent:

        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              The list of vectors <m>\ve{v}_1</m>, <m>\ve{v}_2</m>,
              <m>\ldots</m>, <m>\ve{v}_n</m> is linearly dependent.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Either <m>\ve{v}_1 = \ve{0}</m>,
              or for some <m>r \in \{2, 3, \ldots,
              n\}</m>, <m>\ve{v}_r</m> is a linear combination of <m>\ve{v}_1</m>,
              <m>\ve{v}_2</m>, <m>\ldots</m>, <m>\ve{v}_{r-1}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </proposition>

  <proof>
    <p>
      (1) <m>\Rightarrow</m> (2).
      Suppose that the list <m>\ve{v}_1</m>, <m>\ve{v}_2</m>,
      <m>\ldots</m>, <m>\ve{v}_n</m> is linearly dependent.
      This means that there are scalars <m>k_1</m>,
      <m>k_2</m>, <m>\ldots</m>, <m>k_n</m>, not all zero, such that
      <men xml:id="lin_dep_lem_first_eqn">
        k_1 \ve{v}_1 + k_2 \ve{v}_2 + \cdots + k_n \ve{v}_n = \ve{0}
      </men>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Let <m>r \in \{1, \,2, \ldots, \, n\}</m> be the largest index such that <m>k_r \neq 0</m>.
      (We are told that not all the <m>k_i</m> are zero, so this makes sense.)
      If <m>r=1</m>,
      then <xref ref="lin_dep_lem_first_eqn" /> is simply the equation
      <me>
        k_1 \ve{v}_1 = \ve{0},  \mbox{where }  k_1 \neq 0
      </me>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Therefore <m>\ve{v}_1 = \ve{0}</m> by <xref ref="dichotomy_lem">Lemma</xref>,
      and we are done.
      On the other hand, suppose <m>r \neq 1</m>.
      Then <xref ref="lin_dep_lem_first_eqn" /> becomes the equation
      <me>
        k_1 \ve{v}_1 + k_2 \ve{v}_2 + \cdots + k_r \ve{v}_r = \ve{0},  \mbox{where }  k_r \neq 0
      </me>.
    </p>

    <p>
      By dividing by <m>k_r</m>,
      we can now solve for <m>\ve{v}_r</m> in terms of the preceding vectors <m>\ve{v}_1</m>,
      <m>\ve{v}_2</m>, <m>\ldots</m>, <m>\ve{v}_{r-1}</m>:
      <me>
        \therefore \ve{v}_r = - \frac{k_1}{k_r} \ve{v}_1 - \frac{k_2}{k_r} \ve{v}_2 - \cdots - \frac{k_{r-1}}{k_r} \ve{v}_{r-1} \, 
      </me>.
    </p>

    <p>
      (2) <m>\Rightarrow</m> (1).
      If <m>\ve{v}_1 = \ve{0}</m>,
      then the list of vectors <m>\ve{v}_1</m>,
      <m>\ve{v}_2</m>, <m>\ldots</m>,
      <m>\ve{v}_n</m> is certainly linearly dependent by <xref ref="remark_about_lin_dependence">Remark</xref>.
      On the other hand,
      suppose that for some <m>r \in \{2, 3, \ldots, n\}</m>,
      <m>\ve{v}_r</m> is a linear combination of the preceding vectors, that is
      <me>
        \ve{v}_r = a_1 \ve{v}_1 + a_2 \ve{v}_2 + \cdots + a_{r-1} \ve{v}_{r-1}
      </me>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Then clearly
      <me>
        a_1 \ve{v}_1 + a_2 \ve{v}_2 + \cdots + a_{r-1} \ve{v}_{r-1} - \ve{v}_r + 0 \ve{v}_{r+1} + \cdots + 0 \ve{v}_n = \ve{0}
      </me>
      which shows that the list of vectors <m>\ve{v}_1</m>,
      <m>\ve{v}_2</m>, <m>\ldots</m>,
      <m>\ve{v}_n</m> is not linearly independent,
      since not all the coefficients are zero above <mdash /> in particular the coefficient of <m>\ve{v}_r</m> is <m>-1</m>.
    </p>
  </proof>

  <assemblage>
    <p>
      I call this the <sq>Linear Combination of Preceding Vectors Proposition</sq>.
      You should give all your theorems names,
      it helps you to remember them and become familiar with them.
    </p>
  </assemblage>

  <example xml:id="app_of_prop_preceding">
    <statement>
      <p>
        We saw in <xref ref="example_about_lin_dep_1">Example</xref>
        that the list of vectors <m>\ve{f}_1 = (-1, \, 2)</m>,
        <m>\ve{f}_2 = (1, \,1)</m>,
        <m>\ve{f}_3 = (2, \, -1)</m> in
        <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> is linearly dependent.
        Therefore, by <xref ref="lin_dependence_prop">Proposition</xref>,
        we must have either:

        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\ve{f}_1 = \ve{0}</m>
              (not the case),
              or
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\ve{f}_2</m> is a scalar multiple of <m>\ve{f}_1</m>
              (not the case),
              or
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\ve{f}_3</m> is a linear combination of
              <m>\ve{f}_1</m> and <m>\ve{f}_2</m>, which is true:
              <me>
                \ve{f}_3 = - \ve{f}_1 + \ve{f}_2
              </me>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <proposition xml:id="bumping_off_lemma">
    <title>Bumping Off Proposition</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose <m>\basis{L} = \left\{ \ve{l}_1, \ve{l}_2, \ldots, \ve{l}_m \right\}</m> is a linearly independent list of vectors in a vector space <m>V</m>,
        and that <m>\basis{S} = \left\{ \ve{s}_1, \ve{s}_2, \ldots, \ve{s}_n \right\}</m> spans <m>V</m>.
        Then <m>m \leq n</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </proposition>

  <proof>
    <p>
      Start with the original spanning list of vectors
      <men>
        \basis{S} = \left\{ \,\,  \ve{s}_1, \ve{s}_2, \ldots, \ve{s}_n \right\}
      </men>
      and consider the <sq>bloated</sq> list
      <men xml:id="bloated_list">
        \basis{S}' = \left\{\ve{l}_1, \ve{s}_1, \ve{s}_2, \cdots, \ve{s}_n \right\}
      </men>
    </p>

    <p>
      Since <m>\ve{l}_1</m> is a linear combination of the <m>\ve{s}_i</m>,
      this list is linearly dependent by <xref ref="crit_ind">Remark</xref>.
      Thus, by <xref ref="lin_dependence_prop">Proposition</xref>
      (Linear Combination of Preceding Vectors),
      one of the <m>\ve{s}</m>-vectors, say <m>\ve{s}_r</m>,
      can be expressed as a linear combination of the preceding vectors.
      We can then remove <m>\ve{s}_r</m> from the list (<sq>bump it off</sq>),
      and the resulting list
      <men>
        \basis{S}_1 :=  \left\{\ve{l}_1, \ve{s}_1, \ve{s}_2, \cdots, \hat{\ve{s}_r}, \cdots, \ve{s}_n \right\} \qquad \mbox{(\(\ve{s}_r\) omitted)}
      </men>
      still spans <m>V</m>.
      We can go on in this way,
      each time transferring another one of the <m>\ve{l}</m>-vectors into the list,
      and removing another one of the <m>\ve{s}</m>-vectors,
      to arrive at a new spanning list <m>\basis{S}_2</m>,
      <m>\basis{S}_3</m>, <m>\basis{S}_4</m>, and so on,
      where list <m>\basis{S}_k</m> has <m>(n-k)</m> <m>\ve{s}</m>-vectors.
    </p>

    <p>
      Suppose <m>m > n</m>.
      Then the list <m>\basis{S}_n</m> will consist only of <m>\ve{l}</m>-vectors,
      <me>
        \basis{S}_n: \,\, \ve{l}_1, \ve{l}_2, \ldots, \ve{l}_n
      </me>
      and it spans <m>V</m> by construction.
      But there are still some <m>\ve{l}</m>-vectors <m>\ve{l}_{n+1}, \ldots \ve{l}_{m}</m> left over!
      This means that <m>\ve{l}_{n+1}</m> is a linear combination of the vectors in <m>\basis{S}_n</m>,
      which contradicts the fact that the list
      <m>\left\{\ve{l}_1, \ve{l}_2, \ldots, \ve{l}_m \right\}</m> was linearly independent.
      So we cannot have <m>m > n</m> and hence <m>m \leq n</m>.
    </p>
  </proof>

  <exercises>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Show that the list of vectors
        <m>(2, \, 3, \, 1)</m>, <m>(1, \, -1, \, 2)</m>,
        <m>(7, \, 3, \, c)</m> is linearly dependent in
        <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> if and only if <m>c=8</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="x2_by_2_matrices_lin_dep">
    <statement>
      <p>
        The list of vectors in <m>\Mat_{2,2}</m> given by
         <me>
\ve{v}_1 = \begin{bmatrix}
1 &amp; 2 \\
1 &amp; 1
\end{bmatrix},\,
\ve{v}_2 = \begin{bmatrix}
1 &amp; 0 \\
-2 &amp; 1
\end{bmatrix},\,
\ve{v}_3 = \begin{bmatrix}
1 &amp; 0 \\
2 &amp; 3
\end{bmatrix},\,
\ve{v}_4 = \begin{bmatrix}
0 &amp; 3 \\
1 &amp; -1
\end{bmatrix},\,
\ve{v}_5 = \begin{bmatrix}
1 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 1
\end{bmatrix}
      </me>
        is linearly independent
        (you will prove this in <xref ref="checking_matrices_lin_dep">Exercise</xref>,
        but for the sake of this question you may assume it to be true).
        Go through the same steps as in <xref ref="app_of_prop_preceding">Example</xref>
        to find the first vector in the list which is either the zero vector or a linear combination of the preceding vectors.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  </exercises>
</section>

